[
    {
        "content": "<p>I find \"fundamental theorems\" enjoyable, though I don't always understand why people consider some theorems to be \"fundamental\".   I just learned about this one:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Wikipedia, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invariant_subspace#Fundamental_theorem_of_noncommutative_algebra\">Fundamental theorem of noncommutative algebra</a>.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 227502069,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614113933
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It says that if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> is a finite-dimensional complex vector space and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> is a proper subalgebra of the algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>V</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{End}(V)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">d</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of linear transformations of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>, then there's a linear subspace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>⊂</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>⊂</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 \\subset L \\subset V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68354em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72243em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> that's mapped into itself by every element of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 227502331,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614114023
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Wikipedia manages to obfuscate the statement with lots of notation.)</p>",
        "id": 227502396,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614114049
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How do you prove this?  I'd try to prove the contrapositive.  </p>\n<p>Does it only work over the complex numbers, or (some) other fields too?</p>",
        "id": 227502758,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614114189
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I didn't hear about the name \"Fundamental theorem of noncommutative algebra\" before, but the name makes sense, since it is a generalization of the fundamental theorem of algebra in a non-obvious way.</p>\n<p>The theorem follows from the following stronger result (which is more easily memorizable, for me): <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/q/3038644\">an algebra representation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>V</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi : A \\to \\mathrm{End}(V)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">d</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is absolutely irreducible if and only if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span></span></span></span> is surjective</a>. Over an algebraically closed field, irreducible and absolutely irreducible are the same thing, so if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span></span></span></span> is not surjective, then there is a proper subrepresentation, corresponding to a subspace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>⊂</mo><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L \\subset V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72243em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊂</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> that is preserved under the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>-action.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/a/3038735\">proof</a> of this stronger result contains a proof of the \"fundamental theorem of noncommutative algebra\".</p>\n<p>I think that the result holds if and only if the field is algebraically closed. Suppose that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> is not algebraically closed, then I believe that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>L</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L \\subseteq \\mathrm{End}(L)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">d</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> gives a counterexample, for any finite extension <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L/K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 227570584,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1614158895
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, this is great!  What does \"absolutely irreducible\" mean?   My guess: irreducible after passing to the algebraic closure.   (Any field extension <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L/K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> should let us extend a representation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>V</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi: A \\to \\mathrm{End}(V)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">d</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of algebras over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> to one over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><msub><mo>⊗</mo><mi>L</mi></msub><mi>K</mi><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>V</mi><msub><mo>⊗</mo><mi>L</mi></msub><mi>K</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\otimes_L K \\to \\mathrm{End}(V \\otimes_L K)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">L</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">E</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">d</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">L</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.)</p>",
        "id": 227626102,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614183704
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, that guess was right - I clicked on your link and that's what it says.</p>",
        "id": 227626409,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614183799
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The proof is so slick!  I was vaguely imagining a proof not using any big theorems, and it seemed like it would be very hard.  Artin-Wedderburn is so great... that's the theorem <em>I</em> might call the fundamental theorem of noncommutative algebra.</p>",
        "id": 227628496,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614184422
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Why would the Artin-Wedderburn theorem be the fundamental theorem?</p>",
        "id": 227628810,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1614184517
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's just my favorite theorem about noncommutative algebra.   I don't really take this \"fundamental theorem\" concept seriously, but maybe I could argue that Artin-Wedderburn is the \"fundamental theorem of semisimple algebras\".</p>",
        "id": 227630102,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614184931
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It makes everything about semisimple algebras much easier.</p>",
        "id": 227632074,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614185651
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And representation theory of course.</p>",
        "id": 227632358,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1614185756
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right, when combined with this version of Maschke's theorem: for any finite group G and field k whose characteristic does not divide the order of G, the group algebra k[G] is semisimple.     (Or various other theorems...)</p>",
        "id": 227632854,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1614185903
    }
]